03226nmm a2200505Ia 9780520919198DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231996cau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1241950614  a97805209191987 a10.1525/97805209191982doi  a(DE-B1597)543410  a(OCoLC)1149401589  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a306.7660952qOCoLC220/eng/202311201 aLeupp, Gary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMale Colors :bThe Construction of Homosexuality in Tokugawa Japan /cGary Leupp.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©1996  a1 online resource (317 p.) :b32 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTokugawa Japan ranks with ancient Athens as a society that not only tolerated, but celebrated, male homosexual behavior. Few scholars have seriously studied the subject, and until now none have satisfactorily explained the origins of the tradition or elucidated how its conventions reflected class structure and gender roles. Gary P. Leupp fills the gap with a dynamic examination of the origins and nature of the tradition. Based on a wealth of literary and historical documentation, this study places Tokugawa homosexuality in a global context, exploring its implications for contemporary debates on the historical construction of sexual desire.Combing through popular fiction, law codes, religious works, medical treatises, biographical material, and artistic treatments, Leupp traces the origins of pre-Tokugawa homosexual traditions among monks and samurai, then describes the emergence of homosexual practices among commoners in Tokugawa cities. He argues that it was "nurture" rather than "nature" that accounted for such conspicuous male/male sexuality and that bisexuality was more prevalent than homosexuality. Detailed, thorough, and very readable, this study is the first in English or Japanese to address so comprehensively one of the most complex and intriguing aspects of Japanese history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMale homosexualityxHistoryxJapan. 0aMale homosexualityzJapanxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919198?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919198423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919198/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles